    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-across"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">ᚔᚐ<unclear reason="worn">ᚊ</unclear>ᚔᚅᚔ</name> <w type="formula" lemma="koi"><g ref="#forfid_X"/>ᚑ<unclear reason="worn">ᚔ</unclear></w> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas"><unclear reason="worn">ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</unclear></w> <w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias"><unclear>ᚋᚒᚉ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ᚑᚔ</supplied></w></persName>                
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-across"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">IA<unclear reason="worn">Q</unclear>INI</name> <w type="formula" lemma="koi"><g ref="#forfid_X" type="interpretation_K"/>O<unclear reason="worn">I</unclear></w> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas"><unclear reason="worn">MAQI</unclear></w> <w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias"><unclear>MUC</unclear><supplied reason="lost">OI</supplied></w></persName>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">IAQINI KOI MAQI MUC[OI]</ab>
            </div>
            <!--<div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>-->
            <div type="translation">
                <p>The presence of formula words KOI, MAQI and possible MUCOI suggests that the inscription might have been commemmorative.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>The personal name here may be formed from <distinct xml:lang="sga">iach</distinct>, gen. of <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/20128">éo</ref></distinct> 'salmon', plus a diminutive suffix (Ziegler 1994, 186). Hypercorrect Q for C is also found, for example, in (I-MEA-001) INEQAGLAS (Enechglas) (McManus 1991, 121-2).</p>
                <p>According to McManus (1991, 119), <q>KOI, which is invariably written with the first supplementary character and is alone among formula words in not being attested later, has been explained as a word defining locality, 'here', analogous to HIC IACIT in the British inscriptions though it is never used in these</q>. cf. (I-KID-004) Colbinstown IV: EGNI KOI MAQI MUC[ ... ]. </p>
            </div>
